definition.value: An alternariol hapten that is one of two regioisomeric haptens of the mycotoxin alternariol in which the five-atom carboxylated aliphatic spacer arm is located through the hydroxy group at C-9.
A benzochromenone that is a hapten of the mycotoxin alternariol which incorporates a five-atom carboxylated aliphatic spacer arm located through the hydroxy group at either C-3 or C-9.
An alternariol hapten that is one of two regioisomeric haptens of the mycotoxin alternariol in which the five-atom carboxylated aliphatic spacer arm is located through the hydroxy group at C-3.
A 2-ethyl-2-hexenal in which the double bond adopts a trans-configuration.
A 2-ethyl-2-hexenal in which the double bond adopts a cis-configuration.

A triterpenoid that is (1S)-2,2-dimethyl-4-methylidenecyclohexanol which is substituted at position 3 by a (6E,10E,14E)-2,6,10,15-tetramethylheptadeca-2,6,10,14-tetraen-17-yl group. It was the first monocyclic triterpenoid found in nature and originally isolated from Achillea odorata.
A biphenyl that is 1,1'-biphenyl substituted by a fluoro group at position 4 and a acetylamino group at position 4'. It induces neoplastic lesions in rats.
A member of the class of fluorenes that is 9H-fluorene substituted by a (2-carboxybenzoyl)amino group at position 2.
Chlorophyll a' is the C13(2)-epimer of chlorophyll a.
Divinylchlorophyll a' is the C13(2)-epimer of divinylchlorophyll a.
An L-cysteine derivative that results when maleimide reacts with the thiol group of L-cysteine forming a thioether bond.
An L-alpha-amino acid zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino group of 3-chloro-L-tyrosine; major species at pH 7.3.
Zwitterionic form of 3-bromo-L-tyrosine having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group; major microspecies at pH 7.3.
